[2026-05-31 03:16:56] local.INFO: Recommendation Step Output {"recommendation":{"confidence":0.9,"customer_explanation":"Your kitchen sink is blocked, meaning water isn't draining away properly. This is a very common problem in homes, especially in the kitchen, and needs to be addressed so you can use your sink normally.","diy_checks":["First, check if other sinks, bathtubs, or toilets in your home are also draining slowly or backing up. If only the kitchen sink is affected, the problem is likely localized to that specific drain.","Try using a plunger. Make sure there's enough water in the sink to cover the plunger's rubber cup. Create a good seal over the drain opening and pump the plunger vigorously for 20-30 seconds. Repeat this action a few times.","If plunging doesn't work, you can inspect the U-shaped pipe directly under the sink, which is often called the 'P-trap'. Place a bucket directly underneath it to catch any water. Carefully loosen the large nuts on either side of the trap with an adjustable wrench and remove it. Clean out any food scraps, grease, or other debris you find inside. Once clean, reassemble it tightly, ensuring no leaks."],"estimated_price_max":4000,"estimated_price_min":1500,"immediate_actions":["Stop using the kitchen sink immediately to prevent water from overflowing onto your kitchen floor or into cabinets.","Avoid pouring any more liquids, especially chemical drain cleaners, into the sink. Chemical cleaners can sometimes worsen the blockage, damage your pipes, and pose a health risk if not used correctly."],"issue_type":"drain_blockage","likely_cause":"Most kitchen sink clogs happen because of a gradual build-up of everyday kitchen waste. This includes food scraps (like rice, dal, coffee grounds), cooking oils, ghee, and other greasy substances that solidify inside the drainpipes. Over time, these materials stick together and block the water flow.","preventive_maintenance":["Always use a drain strainer (often called a 'jali' in Nepal) in your sink to catch food particles before they go down the drain. Clean it regularly.","Never pour cooking oil, ghee, or any greasy substances directly down the sink. Let them cool and solidify, then scrape them into the trash bin.","Rinse your sink with hot water after washing dishes, perhaps once a week, to help break down any minor grease build-up.","Consider pouring a mixture of hot water, a quarter cup of baking soda, followed by a cup of vinegar down the drain occasionally as a natural preventative measure. Let it sit for 15-30 minutes, then flush with more hot water. Avoid this if you have recently used chemical drain cleaners."],"professional_steps":["A licensed plumber will typically use a specialized tool called a plumbing snake (or drain auger) to physically break through and remove the blockage deep inside the pipe.","For very stubborn clogs or recurring issues, they might use a high-pressure water jetting machine to thoroughly clean the inside of the pipes, removing all build-up.","They will also inspect your drain system for any underlying issues that could be causing repeated blockages, such as damaged or improperly sloped pipes."],"recommended_service":"Professional drain cleaning and blockage removal.","required_tools":["Plunger","Bucket","Adjustable wrench","Flashlight","Gloves"],"risk_level":"medium","safety_precautions":["Before attempting to clean the P-trap or any part of your plumbing, make sure to shut off the main water supply to your house or at least the stopcock under the sink to prevent accidental water flow.","Never mix different chemical drain cleaners, as this can create dangerous fumes and splashes. It's generally best to avoid them altogether, especially in older plumbing systems common in Nepal, as they can corrode pipes.","Wear sturdy rubber gloves to protect your hands when dealing with dirty drain water or inspecting the P-trap.","Be careful when handling tools like an adjustable wrench. Do not apply excessive force that might damage your pipes or fittings."],"summary":"Your kitchen sink is clogged, which means water isn't draining. This is commonly caused by food and grease build-up. While you can try some safe DIY steps like plunging or cleaning the P-trap, if the clog persists, you'll need a professional plumber to clear it. The estimated cost for this service is between NPR 1500 to NPR 4000, depending on how severe and deep the blockage is. This issue has a medium urgency and risk level.","urgency":"medium","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash"}} 
