[2026-05-31 18:09:40] local.INFO: Recommendation Step Output {"recommendation":{"confidence":0.8,"customer_explanation":"You have water leaking from or around your overhead water tank. This means water is escaping where it shouldn't, which can waste water and potentially damage your roof, walls, or ceiling over time. Even small leaks can become bigger problems if not addressed.","diy_checks":["Carefully check all pipes connected to your water tank (the pipe bringing water in, the pipe taking water out to your house, and the overflow pipe) for any visible drips, wet spots, or signs of moisture.","Inspect the base and sides of your water tank itself for any cracks, holes, or constant sweating that might indicate a leak.","Look at the overflow pipe. If water is constantly dripping or flowing from it even when your tank is not full, it could mean the float valve inside the tank is faulty and needs adjustment or replacement.","Gently feel around the joints and valves where pipes connect to the tank for any dampness."],"estimated_price_max":7000,"estimated_price_min":1500,"immediate_actions":["If the leak is significant or getting worse, try to shut off the main water supply to your house, or at least the valve that fills the overhead tank. This will stop more water from leaking out.","Place buckets, pans, or old cloths directly under the leaking area to collect the water and prevent it from spreading or causing further damage to your property."],"issue_type":"pipe_leak","likely_cause":"The leak is most likely coming from loose connections where pipes join the tank, a damaged overflow pipe, a cracked pipe section (like the outlet pipe), or a small crack or defect in the body of the water tank itself. Sometimes, the internal float valve that tells the tank when to stop filling can malfunction, causing water to constantly flow into the tank and then out through the overflow pipe.","preventive_maintenance":["Regularly inspect your overhead water tank and all connected pipes, especially before and after the monsoon season, for any signs of dampness, drips, or visible wear and tear.","Ensure your tank is installed on a flat, stable, and strong surface to prevent uneven pressure or stress on the tank body and its connections, which can lead to cracks.","Avoid placing heavy objects on top of the tank or accidentally hitting it, as this can cause cracks or damage.","Consider having the float valve inside your tank checked by a plumber every few years to make sure it's working correctly and not causing constant overflow."],"professional_steps":["A professional plumber will carefully inspect the entire water tank system, including all inlet, outlet, and overflow pipes, as well as the tank body itself, to precisely find the source of the leak.","They will use their experience to determine if the leak is due to a faulty fitting, a damaged section of pipe, a valve that isn't working, or a crack in the tank.","Depending on what they find, they might tighten loose fittings, replace a damaged pipe section or valve, or repair a minor crack in the tank using specialized sealing materials.","If the tank itself is severely cracked, very old, or beyond repair, they might recommend replacing the entire tank, though this is less common for minor leaks."],"recommended_service":"Leak Repair for Overhead Water Tank","required_tools":["Bucket","Flashlight","Dry cloths or towels","Adjustable wrench (if you intend to gently check for loose pipe fittings, but be very cautious)"],"risk_level":"medium","safety_precautions":["Always shut off the main water supply to the tank before attempting any inspection or temporary fix to prevent more water damage.","Be extremely careful when working at heights around the overhead tank. Always use a stable ladder or platform, and if you feel unsafe, call a professional.","Do not try to forcefully tighten pipes or fittings if you are unsure, as this can cause more damage and worsen the leak.","Avoid touching any electrical wiring, switches, or appliances near the wet area to prevent the risk of electric shock.","If you find a significant crack in the tank body, do not attempt to patch it yourself with basic materials, as it might fail and cause a much larger and more damaging leak."],"summary":"There's a water leak near your overhead tank. It's important to find and fix this quickly to save water and prevent damage to your home. The cost will depend on what's causing the leak. We recommend calling a qualified plumber to check it out properly.","urgency":"medium","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash"}} 
