overflow pipe. If water is constantly dripping or flowing from it even when your tank is not full, it could mean the float valve inside the tank is faulty and needs adjustment or replacement.","Gently feel around the joints and valves where pipes connect to the tank for any dampness."],"required_tools":["Bucket","Flashlight","Dry cloths or towels","Adjustable wrench (if you intend to gently check for loose pipe fittings, but be very cautious)"],"professional_steps":["A professional plumber will carefully inspect the entire water tank system, including all inlet, outlet, and overflow pipes, as well as the tank body itself, to precisely find the source of the leak.","They will use their experience to determine if the leak is due to a faulty fitting, a damaged section of pipe, a valve that isn't working, or a crack in the tank.","Depending on what they find, they might tighten loose fittings, replace a damaged pipe section or valve, or repair a minor crack in the tank using specialized sealing materials.","If the tank itself is severely cracked, very old, or beyond repair, they might recommend replacing the entire tank, though this is less common for minor leaks."],"safety_precautions":["Always shut off the main water supply to the tank before attempting any inspection or temporary fix to prevent more water damage.","Be extremely careful when working at heights around the overhead tank. Always use a stable ladder or platform, and if you feel unsafe, call a professional.","Do not try to forcefully tighten pipes or fittings if you are unsure, as this can cause more damage and worsen the leak.","Avoid touching any electrical wiring, switches, or appliances near the wet area to prevent the risk of electric shock.","If you find a significant crack in the tank body, do not attempt to patch it yourself with basic materials, as it might fail and cause a much larger and more damaging leak."],"preventive_maintenance":["Regularly inspect your overhead water tank and all connected pipes, especially before and after the monsoon season, for any signs of dampness, drips, or visible wear and tear.","Ensure your tank is installed on a flat, stable, and strong surface to prevent uneven pressure or stress on the tank body and its connections, which can lead to cracks.","Avoid placing heavy objects on top of the tank or accidentally hitting it, as this can cause cracks or damage.","Consider having the float valve inside your tank checked by a plumber every few years to make sure it's working correctly and not causing constant overflow."]}} 
